                    <outline text="Apache Features #slide ">
                        <outline text="Server Side Programming Language Support">
                            <outline text="Apache supports some common language interfaces which include Perl, Python, Tcl, and PHP. It also supports a variety of popular authentication modules like mod_auth, mod_access, mod_digest and many others."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="IPv6 Support">
                            <outline text="On systems where IPv6 is supported by the underlying Apache Portable Runtime library, Apache gets IPv6 listening sockets by default. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Virtual Hosting">
                            <outline text="Apache will allow one installation instance to serve multiple websites. For instance one Apache installation can serve sse.afnog.org, ws.afnog.org etc"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Simplified configuration"/>
                        <outline text="Native Windows NT Unicode Support"/>
                        <outline text="More at: http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.2/new_features_2_0.html  "/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Apache and IPv6 #slide ">
                        <outline text="Apache supports IPv4 and IPv6 by default"/>
                        <outline text="Set the listen option to port 80 will listen for both IPv4 and IPv6"/>
                        <outline text="listen option with IPv4 and IPv6 specific addresses will invoke different sockets for each protocol"/>
                        <outline text="Listen 196.200.219.xx:80"/>
                        <outline text="Listen [2001:43f8:0:219:196:200:219:xx]:80"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Virtual Hosting #slide ">
                        <outline text="Apache Provides multiple options of virtual hosting and scales"/>
                        <outline text="Name Based virtual hosts "/>
                        <outline text="IP Based Virtual Hosts"/>
                        <outline text="Aliases"/>
                        <outline text="It's recommended to use name based virtual hosting over IP based hosting in virtual hosting configuration"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Installing PHP and MySQL #slide ">
                        <outline text="PHP and Mysql implementations have increased driven mainly by development requests"/>
                        <outline text="LAMP and WAMP are the most common implementations "/>
                        <outline text="Installation via “dkpg” and “apt-get” and relatively straight forward"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Starting Apache #slide ">
                        <outline text="Startup scripts are located at">
                            <outline text="`/etc/init.d/`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Take a look in startup script">
                            <outline text="`/etc/init.d/apache2`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Add Apache to startup">
                            <outline text="`update-rc.d apache2 enable`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Run">
                            <outline text="`$ /etc/init.d/apache2 restart`"/>
                            <outline text="`$ sudo service apache2 start`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Restart">
                            <outline text="`$ sudo service apache2 restart`"/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Start Apache! #slide ">
                        <outline text="`/etc/init.d/apache2 start`"/>
                        <outline text="Check that you can access `http://your.ip.add.ress` in your browser"/>
                        <outline text="Check that you can access `https://your.ip.add.ress` in your browser, and that you get a certificate warning"/>
                        <outline text="Click on the padlock icon in your browser and check that the certificate details are correct"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Apache SSL #slide ">
                        <outline text="Secure Socket Layer (SSL) port is 443"/>
                        <outline text="SSL is important to protect communication between client browser and web-server"/>
                        <outline text="Requires the creation of SSL certificates and Certificate Signing Requests (CSR)"/>
                        <outline text="For integrity, SSL certificates are signed by a Certificate Authority’s (CA) such as Verisign"/>
                        <outline text="Self signed Certificates will also work but your browser will not trust it and will give a warning to users (which most don’t read)"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="How SSL Works #slide ">
                        <outline text="Each SSL certificate has a Public and Private key"/>
                        <outline text="The Public Key is used to encrypt (digitally sign) the information"/>
                        <outline text="The Public Key is accessible to everyone"/>
                        <outline text="The private Key is used to decipher the information"/>
                        <outline text="The private should be not be disclosed"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Role of Certificate Authority #slide ">
                        <outline text="There are a number of CA that certify certificates"/>
                        <outline text="Most browsers have pre-included public Keys from the CA’s"/>
                        <outline text="A CA certified certificate will have validation information signed by the CA’s private key"/>
                        <outline text="The browser will decrypt the validation information using the public key and verify that the certificate is certified by the CA"/>
                        <outline text="If this fails a warning is given"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Apache installation on Debian #slide ">
                        <outline text="Apache can be installed from APT-GET">
                            <outline text="`apt-get install apache2`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Can be installed from dpkg  "/>
                        <outline text="Or from source if one requires a more recent version than what's on Debian source list"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="File System Layout #slide ">
                        <outline text="Important Apache config files and directories:">
                            <outline text="`/var/www/index.html` or  `/var/www/html/index.html`"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="SSL Configuration:">
