                <outline text="Cryptographic Currency #h" complete="true" heading="1">
                    <outline text="note: #!slide used for sections that may be too long to fit on a single slide:"/>
                    <outline text="Origins of Money #h " heading="2" colorLabel="1">
                        <outline text="What is money? #!slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="Hunter-Gatherer tribe:">
<outline text="A group of hunters kill a mammoth"/>
<outline text="The mammoth is cut up and meat is taken home to feed the tribe"/>
<outline text="The tribe &quot;owes&quot; each hunter for his part in killing the mammoth"/>
<outline text="Debt is settled by share of meat"/>
<outline text="It is easy to remember who is owed in a small group"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Invention of agriculture:">
<outline text="Domestication of plants and animals."/>
<outline text="Hunting declines - people settle - cities founded."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Specialisation of trades:">
<outline text="Farmers, "/>
<outline text="Carpenters"/>
<outline text="Metal smiths…etc."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="There are too many people now for informal debts easily to be remembered/enforced."/>
                            <outline text="Barter systems develop:">
<outline text="Exchange of eggs for apples."/>
<outline text="Grain for swords…etc. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Aristotle (384-322BC) on the origin of money:">
<outline text="Every commodity has a primary (original) use and a secondary use as an item of barter."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;What is money 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;What is money 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="What makes good money? #slide ">
                            <outline text="According to Aristotle, the commodity must:">
<outline text="1. Be durable">
    <outline text="Must not fade, corrode etc."/>
</outline>
<outline text="2. Be portable">
    <outline text="Must have a high worth relative to its weight   and size"/>
</outline>
<outline text="3. Be divisible/fungible">
    <outline text="May be separated, re-combined,   exchanged, replaced without affecting   value."/>
</outline>
<outline text="4. Have intrinsic value">
    <outline text="The value of money must be independent   of   anything except the money itself."/>
    <outline text="Usually linked to its scarcity."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Gold as money #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="1. Durable - YES">
<outline text="Gold remains gold (though gold coins   can be chipped – original reason why   coins have “milled” edges)."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="2. Portable - YES">
<outline text="Gold is valuable relative to its weight.   Gold coins can be carried"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="3. Divisible/fungible - YES">
<outline text="Different sized coins/ingots can be cast  and recast."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="4. Intrinsic value - PARTIALLY">
<outline text="Valueof gold depends on the amount of gold there is in circulation. (As more gold is mined, value of existing gold falls.)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Gold used to mint gold coins of standard weight/purity – payees know they are getting the amount of gold they think they are."/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Gold as money&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="YouTube Videos #slide ">
                            <outline text="Sir Martyn Poliakoff talking about the gold in the Bank of England…">
<outline text="[https://](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTtf5s2HFkA)[www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTtf5s2HFkA](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTtf5s2HFkA)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Professor Lawrence White on the “Gold Standard”…">
<outline text="[https://](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LdyHso5iSZI)[www.youtube.com/watch?v=LdyHso5iSZI](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LdyHso5iSZI)"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Virtualization of Money #h " heading="2" colorLabel="4">
                        <outline text="Fiat Money and Virtual Money #slide">
                            <outline text="Gold replaced by promissory tokens/banknotes issued by governments and banks.">
<outline text="Under “gold standard” these could be exchanged for gold coin. "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="“Fiat” system nowadays more common.">
<outline text="debt acknowledged, but not actually backed up with gold."/>
<outline text="Value of notes/base-metal coins depends on authority of issuer, which must be trusted."/>
<outline text="Can be counterfeited! (Counterfeit £1 coins are becoming a nuisance!)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Now however…">
<outline text="most money is “virtual” – it does not exist even as fiat tokens!"/>
<outline text="Exists as a balance in a bank account – acknowledgment of debt."/>
<outline text="Most money is now merely information. (As it originally was!)"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Money as Information #slide ">
                            <outline text="We no longer have physical tokens to record debt"/>
                            <outline text="Their properties must be replicated virtually:">
<outline text="Integrity">
    <outline text="Total amount of money must be conserved during every transaction. (Money may not be “double spent”)."/>
    <outline text="Transaction must be irrevocable; payer may not (unilaterally) reverse transaction afterwards."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Scarcity">
    <outline text="“New” money cannot be created by anyone without appropriate authority."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="These features enforced by a trusted financial institution/ authority, which all participants trust."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="YouTube Video... #slide ">
                            <outline text="“Money as Debt” – documentary by Paul Grignon">
<outline text="–[https://](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqvKjsIxT_8)[www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqvKjsIxT_8](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jqvKjsIxT_8)"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Centralized Authority #slide ">
                            <outline text="“Payment” involves an authorized instruction to bank to transfer funds from one account to another.">
<outline text="Credit/Debit Cards"/>
<outline text="Cheques/Wire Transfer"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Contrast to paying with coins, banknotes etc.">
<outline text="These are issued by a central authority, but transferred on a “peer-to-peer” basis."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Decentralized Currency #slide ">
                            <outline text="Peer-to-Peer system – no centralized authority.">
<outline text="Mimics buying/selling with gold coins (also peer-to-peer)."/>
<outline text="We need an electronic equivalent to gold coins."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Early attempts: “Hashcash”, “b-money”."/>
                            <outline text="Bitcoin introduced in 2009 by “Setoshi Nakamoto”">
<outline text="This is not his real name."/>
<outline text="Sounds Japanese, but he is believed to be English or Norwegian."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="To understand how this works, we must first be sure to understand a few cryptographic concepts."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Cryptographic Foundations of Bitcoin #h " heading="2" colorLabel="2">
                        <outline text="Cryptographic Foundations #slide ">
                            <outline text="To understand how this works, we must understand three basic cryptographic concepts:">
<outline text="Hash Functions"/>
<outline text="Digital Signatures"/>
<outline text="Proof-of-Work (PoW)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="The first two will be familiar to you from the previous lecture, but I shall recap..."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Hash Functions #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="A deterministic function H, mapping bit string of arbitrary length to fixed length string."/>
                            <outline text="Output bits are seemingly random."/>
                            <outline text="Algorithm needs to be:">
<outline text="Fast - many hashes may be generated in a very short time."/>
<outline text="“Collision resistant”: chance of 2 inputs producing identical output very very small."/>
<outline text="“Pre-image resistant”: infeasible to find input given output."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Hash demo:  [http://](http://www.xorbin.com/tools/sha256-hash-calculator)[www.xorbin.com/tools/sha256-hash-calculator](http://www.xorbin.com/tools/sha256-hash-calculator)"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Hash functions&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Digital Signatures (RSA Type) #!slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="Public Key Cryptography: keys are created in pairs:"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Digital signatures 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Messages encrypted using KU can only be decrypted using KR."/>
                            <outline text="Messages encrypted using KR can only be decrypted using KU."/>
                            <outline text="Neither key can (feasibly) be inferred from the other."/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Digital signatures 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Digital signatures 3&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Digital signatures 4&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Proof-of-Work (PoW) Problem #!slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;PoW problem 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Forces the challenged party to “do work” – if x=40, he/she must perform about 2^40=1,000,000,000,000 hashing operations."/>
                            <outline text="Imposes a “cost” on the challenged party, deterring him/her from over-using/ abusing services (if proof-of-work needed before access given). "/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;PoW problem 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Only one hashing operation is needed to check that this work has been done."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="YouTube Video">
                            <outline text="Khan Academy – explanation of PoW">
<outline text="[https](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9V1bipPkCTU)[://](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9V1bipPkCTU)[www.youtube.com/watch?v=9V1bipPkCTU](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9V1bipPkCTU)"/>
<outline text="This video doesn’t really add much to what I’ve said, but you may want an alternative description. "/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Bitcoin Transactions #h " heading="2" colorLabel="5">
                        <outline text="“Bitcoin” – Two Meanings #slide ">
                            <outline text="Bitcoin (BTC) is a unit of currency (has an exchange rate with £, $, yen etc.">
<outline text="Typically 1 bitcoin = $165 (Subject to huge fluctuations)"/>
<outline text="There are lots of different denominations of units – e.g. thousandths and millions of bitcoins."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Bitcoin is the peer-to-peer protocol for the exchange of bitcoins between parties (players).">
<outline text="Also facilitates the “mining” of bitcoins."/>
<outline text="Participants compete to record “blocks” of transactions."/>
<outline text="Winners rewarded with newly “minted” bitcoins."/>
<outline text="Like mining gold – introduces a mechanism for devaluation"/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="What is a Bitcoin? #slide ">
                            <outline text="A virtual “coin” that can be exchanged."/>
                            <outline text="Exists as a chain of digital signatures representing all the transactions in the coin’s history."/>
                            <outline text="Validated checked by verifying of these signatures."/>
                            <outline text="Contains a “bitcoin address” = public key of the coin’s owner.">
<outline text="–Owner has the corresponding private key."/>
<outline text="–Only owner can sign an instruction to transfer that bitcoin to a new owner."/>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Bitcoin Transfer #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Bitcoin transfer&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Bitcoin Verification #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Bitcoin verification&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="“Double Spending” #!slide  " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Double spending 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Double spending 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Both “owners” can also verify all earlier transactions in that bitcoin’s history, and each believe they are its genuine owner. There is no mechanism to detect the previous owner’s fraud."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="The “Block Chain” and Bitcoin Mining #h " heading="2" colorLabel="3">
                        <outline text="The Public Ledger #slide ">
                            <outline text="Record of all bitcoin transactions."/>
                            <outline text="Must be kept up-to-date and agreed upon by all players. "/>
                            <outline text="Receiver of a bitcoin must be able to verify from the ledger:">
<outline text="That the payer genuinely owned the bitcoin with which he/she paid."/>
<outline text="The payer did not use that same bitcoin to pay someone else."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="This “ledger” may be:">
<outline text="Held/maintained by a centralized authority.">
    <outline text="Older solution."/>
</outline>
<outline text="Maintained collectively by the entire community.">
    <outline text="Newer solution implemented in Bitcoin algorithm."/>
</outline>
<outline text="The Bitcoin “ledger” is called the “Block Chain”.">
    <outline text="Maintained/updated by “Bitcoin Miners”."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Bitcoin Mining #!slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Bitcoin mining 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Bitcoin mining 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Bitcoin mining 3&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="The &quot;Block Chain&quot; #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;The block chain&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Copy of the Block Chain is stored by all “Players” (participants in the Bitcoin network). Can take ages to download!"/>
                            <outline text="Each block contains a hash of its predecessor – anyone can verify no preceding block was modified!"/>
                            <outline text="Links only point backwards – never forward. Forward path may not be unique!"/>
                            <outline text="Forward path may form a Branching Tree – rival groups of miners attempting to add the next branch. (We’ll talk about how this is resolved later. For the moment, just be aware of this problem.)"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Mining: The PoW Problem #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Mining PoW&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Rival Block-Chain Branches #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Rival block-chain branches&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Resolving Rival Branches #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Resolving rival branches&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Branch B becomes the longest – everyone accepts it as the “valid” branch."/>
                            <outline text="Now accepted as next section of blockchain."/>
                            <outline text="Bitcoins “earned” in losing branch are invalid."/>
                            <outline text="Miners working on other branches now switch to work on the winning branch."/>
                            <outline text="Users accept as valid the longest branch they are aware of."/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Bitcoin Inflation #h " heading="2" colorLabel="6">
                        <outline text="Creating Scarcity… #slide " colorLabel="1">
                            <outline text="If bitcoin mining goes on forever…">
<outline text="…the supply of bitcoins will steadily increase, and…"/>
<outline text="…the real value of each existing bitcoin will fall!"/>
<outline text="INFLATION!!">
    <outline text="This is the usual result of the supply of money increasing faster than the quantity of goods available to be bought."/>
</outline>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Solution…">
<outline text="Implement a “law of diminishing returns”"/>
<outline text="Number of reward bitcoins programmed to half every time 210,000 bitcoins are mined."/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Creating scarcity 1&quot;-" colorLabel="3">
<outline text="Estimation (Source: “The Ultimate Guide to Bitcoin” by Michael Miller, Que Publishing, 2015.)"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="-See box for image &quot;Creating scarcity 2&quot;-" colorLabel="3"/>
                            <outline text="Maximum number of bitcoins that will ever exist is 210,000,000."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Transaction Fees #slide ">
                            <outline text="Eventually almost no new bitcoins will be produced.">
<outline text="As if nearly all the gold in the world were mined"/>
<outline text="Rewards for mining more do not cover costs."/>
<outline text="Former “miners” will need a new incentive to continue their work"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="From then onwards, incentives will be provided in the form of “transaction fees” payable by users."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="YouTube Video… #slide ">
                            <outline text="US Philosopher Stefan Molyneux on Bitcoin… ">
<outline text="[https](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4HGVJjqDVk)[://](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4HGVJjqDVk)[www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4HGVJjqDVk](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w4HGVJjqDVk) "/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="Note: I find Molyneaux’s ideas interesting, but I disagree with most of them: please don’t think that by recommending this video I’m advocating Molyneux’s (or anyone else’s) brand of anarcho-capitalism. I’m not!"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Problems to think about… #slide ">
                            <outline text="What happens if a short block chain branch has a “growth-spurt” and overtakes the longest branch? "/>
                            <outline text="What happens if a dishonest person gains more than 50% of processing power on the bitcoin network?"/>
                            <outline text="What about the energy wasted on solving the PoW problem? "/>
                        </outline>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
